==Cover songs==
Dream Theater have covered other artists' work throughout their career. They have performed cover songs live and in studio, with many of those live performances being recorded for official release. ''A Change of Seasons'' features [[Elton John]], [[Deep Purple]], [[Led Zeppelin]], [[Pink Floyd]], [[Kansas (band)|Kansas]], [[Queen (band)|Queen]], [[Journey (band)|Journey]], [[Dixie Dregs]] and [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]] live covers. Through YtseJam Records, the band have also released full album live cover performances of [[Metallica]]'s ''[[Master of Puppets]]'', Iron Maiden's ''[[The Number of the Beast (album)|The Number of the Beast]]'', Pink Floyd's ''[[The Dark Side of the Moon]]'', and Deep Purple's ''[[Made in Japan (Deep Purple album)|Made in Japan]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Covers Series|url=http://www.ytsejamrecords.com/ProductCart/pc/viewCategories.asp?pageStyle=h&idCategory=7|publisher=YtseJam Records|accessdate=July 7, 2012}}</ref> The special edition of ''Black Clouds & Silver Linings'' includes a bonus disc with [[Rainbow (rock band)|Rainbow]], Queen, Dixie Dregs, [[Zebra (American band)|Zebra]], [[King Crimson]], and [[Iron Maiden]] covers. Other notable artists covered by Dream Theater include [[Black Sabbath]], [[Ozzy Osbourne]], [[Pantera]], [[Rush (band)|Rush]], [[the Who]], and [[Yes (band)|Yes]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Covers Series: Uncovered 2003–2005|url=http://www.ytsejamrecords.com/ProductCart/pc/viewPrd.asp?idproduct=35&idcategory=7|publisher=YtseJam Records|accessdate=July 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dream Theater covers Rush's The Camera Eye at Toronto show|url=http://www.rushisaband.com/display.php?id=1930|publisher=Rush Is a Band|accessdate=July 7, 2012}}</ref>

==Logo and imagery==
[[File:Majesty (old name of Dream Theater) (logo).svg|thumb|right|upright|Dream Theater wordmark and "Majesty" symbol]]
Despite the band being forced to change their name, Dream Theater adopted a custom [[logo]] (known as the ''Majesty symbol'') and [[Wordmark (graphic identity)|wordmark]] which has appeared on the vast majority of their promotional material and on the front cover of every Dream Theater studio album. The Majesty symbol is derived from [[Mary, Queen of Scots]]' mark,<ref>The mark used by [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], is available on [http://www.dreamtheater.net/pics/marysymb.jpg DreamTheater.net]. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725012406/http://www.dreamtheater.net/pics/marysymb.jpg |date=July 25, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marie-stuart.co.uk/images/sun%20embroidery.jpg |title=An embroidery showing the Mary, Queen of Scots, symbol in use |date= |accessdate=July 18, 2011}}</ref> which was re-worked by [[Charlie Dominici]] for use on the album artwork for ''[[When Dream and Day Unite]]''.<ref name="What is the 'symbol' DT use">{{cite web|url=http://faq.dtnorway.com/question?questionid=29 |title=What is the 'symbol' DT use? |website=Faq.dtnorway.com |date=November 7, 2003 |accessdate=January 30, 2016}}</ref>

In September 2010, a fan of Dream Theater discovered that all of the letters of "DOMINICI" fit together perfectly into the Majesty symbol.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jfdRfcCe_NM |title=What does Dream Theater, Majesty and Dominici have in common? |publisher=YouTube |date=September 13, 2010 |accessdate=September 28, 2010}}</ref> When Charlie discovered this, he laughed and mentioned that "it only took them 25 years to figure out the 'Dominici Code!'"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dominici.com/forum/index.php?topic=421.0 |title=Someone finally figured out the "Dominici Code!" |publisher=DOMINICI.com Forum |date=September 28, 2010 |accessdate=September 28, 2010}}</ref> This has earlier also been discovered as shown on the comment section of DTFAQ<ref name="What is the 'symbol' DT use"/> and in the DTNorway Podcast Episode 2 from 2008, with Charlie Dominici.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dtnorway.com/podcast.xml |title=Echo's Hill Podcast |publisher=DTNorway |date= |accessdate=July 18, 2011}}</ref>

==Musical style==
[[AllMusic]]'s [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] described Dream Theater's music as a "dense blend of [[progressive rock]] and post-[[Van Halen|Halen]] [[heavy metal music|metal]]".
The band is well noted for being one of the early progenitors of the [[progressive metal]] genre.<ref name= allmusic>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/style/progressive-metal-ma0000002797|title=Progressive Metal|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=December 12, 2010}}</ref> The original members, Mike Portnoy, John Petrucci and John Myung, have strong influences from progressive rock bands such as [[Rush (band)|Rush]], [[Yes (band)|Yes]], and [[Pink Floyd]], heavy metal bands such as [[Iron Maiden]] and [[Judas Priest]], various [[speed metal]] bands, and even the [[glam metal]] of the day.<ref name=rhap>{{cite web|url=http://www.rhapsody.com/dream-theater|last=York|first=Will|work=[[Rhapsody (online music service)|Rhapsody]]|title=Dream Theater|accessdate=December 12, 2010}}</ref> This synthesis created a unique metal that was not traditional of the day: it had distorted guitars and fast riffing, but the music focused more on technical proficiency and precise execution than on heavy metal riffs. The band's music has focused on three main elements: metal, melody, and progressive roots.<ref name= utube>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vlbhILPW80A|title=Dream Theater – Interview – part 1|last=Portnoy|first=Mike|work=TheCrookedStep.com|accessdate=December 12, 2010}}</ref>
Mike Portnoy has also stated that the band's slower songs are in appreciation of artists such as [[Peter Gabriel]], [[U2]], and [[Journey (band)|Journey]].<ref>Greatest Hit (...And 21 Other Pretty Cool Songs) booklet liner notes.</ref>
Dream Theater's music has also been described as [[art rock]].<ref>{{cite_book|title=Legends of Rock Guitar: The Essential Reference of Rock's Greatest Guitarists|author=Pete Prown, Harvey P. Newquist|quote="Dream Theater carved a niche for themselves as an art-rock band with few peers"}}</ref><ref>{{cite_book|title=Disco, Punk, New Wave, Heavy Metal, and More: Music in the 1970s and 1980s|author=Britannica Educational Publishing|quote="Dream Theater also explored a number of stylistic features earlier associated with art rock."}}</ref>

Dream Theater's 2003 album ''[[Train of Thought (Dream Theater album)|Train of Thought]]'' showcased a heavier sound.<ref>{{cite web|first=Thom|last=Jurek |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/train-of-thought-mw0000319323 |title=Train of Thought – Dream Theater &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |website=[[AllMusic]] |date=November 14, 2003 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> This decision was inspired by the positive feedback received from their previous heavier songs on stage.<ref>As discussed by John Petrucci in the 20th Anniversary Documentary "The Score So Far", found on the [[Score (Dream Theater album)|Score]] DVD</ref>
1999's ''[[Metropolis Pt. 2: Scenes from a Memory]]'' was praised for its display of old-fashioned progressive rock,<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/metropolis-pt-2-scenes-from-a-memory-mw0000251583 |title=Metropolis, Pt. 2: Scenes from a Memory – Dream Theater &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |website=[[AllMusic]] |date=October 26, 1999 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> and was influenced by classic conceptual rock records such as [[the Beatles]]' ''[[Sgt Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'', [[Pink Floyd]]'s ''[[The Wall]]'' and ''[[The Final Cut (album)|The Final Cut]]'', [[the Who]]'s ''[[Tommy (The Who album)|Tommy]]'', and [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]]'s ''[[The Lamb Lies Down on Broadway]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=muBfZoIsQoA |title=Dream Theater – Making of Scenes From A Memory |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=August 25, 2006 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>

Dream Theater's music occasionally borrows elements of other musical styles including [[symphonic rock]], [[symphonic metal]], {{nowrap|[[arena rock]]}}, [[soft rock]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Lewis |first=Catherine P. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/music/dream-theater-album-review/2014/03/27/9bea0904-b04f-11e3-95e8-39bef8e9a48b_story.html |title=Dream Theater album review |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> and [[classical music]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/john-petrucci-2013-interview/ |title=John Petrucci Of Dream Theater Interview |publisher=Ultimateclassicrock.com |date=October 26, 2013 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>

