'''Notes'''

* Chris Collins was the shortest-serving band member, having only been an official member for a few months; first joining them at the same time as Kevin Moore in the summer of 1986, but parting ways after they did some initial touring following recording their 6-track demo.<ref name="Majesty Demo Liner Notes"></ref>
* In the wake of Charlie Dominici's departure from the band in October and November 1989<ref>{{cite web|last1=Portnoy|first1=Mike|title=MikePortnoy.com Tourography: 10/14/1989 - Bay Shore, Long Island|url=http://mikeportnoy.com/dates/MPTourography/ShowInfo.aspx?showId=27|website=MikePortnoy.com|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Portnoy|first1=Mike|title=MikePortnoy.com Tourography: 11/14/1989 - New York City|url=http://mikeportnoy.com/dates/MPTourography/ShowInfo.aspx?showId=28|website=MikePortnoy.com |accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref> the band worked with several singers on a temporary basis before fully committing to James LaBrie; they first worked with [[John Arch]], though he was not seriously considering joining the band, then John Hendricks, then Steve Stone (who had a one-off live appearance with the band),<ref>{{cite web|last1=Portnoy|first1=Mike|title=MikePortnoy.com Tourography: 07/09/1990 - Bay Shore, Long Island|url=http://mikeportnoy.com/dates/MPTourography/ShowInfo.aspx?showId=29|website=MikePortnoy.com|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref> then finally Chris Cintron, who they were ready to commit to and officially welcome into the band before James LaBrie's audition arrived.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Portnoy|first1=Mike|title=MikePortnoy.com FAQ: "Which vocalists worked with Dream Theater between the time that Charlie was in the band and James joined the band, and in what order?"|url=http://www.mikeportnoy.com/aboutmike/faq/answers/38.aspx#267|website=MikePortnoy.com|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dream Theater - 20th Anniversary Documentary|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LduXtT3edlI&t=18m21s|via=[[YouTube]]|publisher=Rhino Entertainment|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref><!-- NOTE: This YouTube video is an official upload from Rhino. I've chosen to cite this instead of the DVD, since many people may not own the DVD, thus this official upload would be a better one to cite. It's the same content, just more publicly available. -->
* During the 1997-1998 world tour, the band would switch their instruments around for brief "[[Nightmare Cinema (band)|Nightmare Cinema]]" interludes in the concerts; John Myung played the keyboard, Derek Sherinian played the guitar, John Petrucci played the drums, and Mike Portnoy played the bass. They would often cover Perfect Strangers during these segments.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Portnoy|first1=Mike|title=MikePortnoy.com FAQ: "What Is Nightmare Cinema?"|url=http://www.mikeportnoy.com/aboutmike/faq/answers/15.aspx#87|website=MikePortnoy.com|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref>
* In 2004, Charlie Dominici and Derek Sherinian joined the band as a one-off on stage during the encore of the March 6th show as guests, to celebrate the 15th anniversary of the When Dream And Day Unite album.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Portnoy|first1=Mike|title=MikePortnoy.com Tourography: 03/06/2004 Los Angeles, CA, USA|url=http://mikeportnoy.com/dates/MPTourography/ShowInfo.aspx?showId=751|website=MikePortnoy.com The Official Website|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref>

