==Awards and honors==

'''''[[Burrn!]]'' magazine'''

In 2007 Jordan Rudess was awarded "Best Keyboards Player of the Year."

In 2011, ''A Dramatic Turn of Events'' won Best Album and Best Front Cover, while John Petrucci and Jordan Rudess won Best Guitarist and Best Keyboardist, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msopr.com/press-releases/dream-theater-win-big-in-burrn-magazines-2011-awards/|title=DREAM THEATER Win Big In Burrn! Magazine’s 2011 Awards - Mitch Schneider Organization|first=|last=aaron|website=Msopr.com|accessdate=May 12, 2019}}</ref>

'''''[[Guitar World]]'''''

The album ''[[Metropolis Pt. 2: Scenes from a Memory]]'' was ranked No.&nbsp;95 on the magazine's list of the ''100 Greatest Guitar Albums of All Time''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rateyourmusic.com/list/Boggs1027/guitar_worlds_100_greatest_guitar_albums_of_all_time |title=Dream Theater's Metropolis Pt. 2: Scenes from a Memory ranks No.&nbsp;95 on Guitar World's 100 greatest guitar albums of all time |publisher=Rateyourmusic.com |date= |accessdate=July 18, 2011}}</ref>

'''''Total Guitar'''''

John Petrucci won ''Guitarist of the year award'' (2007)

'''[[Ultimate Guitar Archive]]'''

In 2009, Dream Theater were placed on the Top 10 in Ultimate Guitar's ''The Greatest Metal Bands of the Decade''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/columns/features/the_top_ten_bands_of_the_decade_metal_continues_to_rule_supreme.html |title=Ultimate Guitar's Best Metal Bands of the Decade! |publisher=ultimate-guitar.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717154132/http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/columns/features/the_top_ten_bands_of_the_decade_metal_continues_to_rule_supreme.html |archivedate=July 17, 2011 }}</ref>

'''''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'' magazine'''

Dream Theater won ''The Spirit of Prog Award'' at the ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] Roll of Honour 2009'' in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/ArtisanNewsService#p/search/4/bWBma2xE4q4 |title=Канал користувача ArtisanNewsService |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=July 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/iggy-pop-awarded-living-legend-at-classic-rock-roll-of-honour-2009/ |title=Dream Theater won ''The Spirit of Prog Award'' at Classic Rock Roll of Honour 2009! |publisher=Classicrockmagazine.com |accessdate=July 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923220427/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/iggy-pop-awarded-living-legend-at-classic-rock-roll-of-honour-2009/ |archivedate=September 23, 2010 }}</ref> They were also nominated for the ''Album of the Year Award'' for their album, [[Black Clouds & Silver Linings]] in 2009, but lost to [[AC/DC]]'s ''[[Black Ice (album)|Black Ice]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/classic-rock-roll-of-honour-09-nominations/ |title=Classic Rock » Blog Archive » Classic Rock Roll Of Honour ‘09 Nominations! |publisher=Classicrockmagazine.com |date=June 26, 2009 |accessdate=July 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108044300/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/classic-rock-roll-of-honour-09-nominations/ |archivedate=January 8, 2010 }}</ref>

'''''[[Rolling Stone]]'''''

On July 25, 2011, Dream Theater were placed on the list ''"The Best Prog Rock Bands of All Time"'', chosen by the Rolling Stone Magazine's readers poll.<ref name="RollingStone">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/photos/readers-poll-the-best-prog-rock-bands-of-all-time-20110720/0318489 |title=Readers Poll: The Best Prog Rock Bands of All Time |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |author=Greene, Andy |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805023858/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/photos/readers-poll-the-best-prog-rock-bands-of-all-time-20110720/0318489 |archivedate=August 5, 2011 }}</ref>

'''[[MusicRadar]]'''

The MusicRadar readers poll placed Dream Theater amongst ''"The 30 greatest live acts in the world today"'' (as of 2010), peaking at No.&nbsp;5 on the list, .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/the-30-greatest-live-acts-in-the-world-today-462684 |title=The 30 greatest live acts in the world today |publisher=MusicRadar.com |date=June 16, 2011 |accessdate=July 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921122856/http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/the-30-greatest-live-acts-in-the-world-today-462684 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 }}</ref>

John Myung, from August through September 2010, was voted the greatest bassist of all time. In the same time frame, Mike Portnoy was voted the second best drummer ever, losing out to [[Joey Jordison]]. In December 2010, James LaBrie was voted the 15th best frontman of all time (with [[Axl Rose]] coming first and [[Freddie Mercury]] in second). Jordan Rudess was voted the best keyboardist of all time in a poll conducted from June to July this year, with John Petrucci coming second in a shred-guitarist poll conducted in May this year (losing out to [[Al Di Meola]]).

[[John Petrucci]] listed as "Best Prog Rock Guitarist in the World" in 2020, by Music Radar <ref name="MR" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Prog Rock Best Guitarist int the World |url=https://www.musicradar.com/news/the-10-best-prog-guitarists-in-the-world-today |website=MusicRadar}}</ref>

'''''[[Metal Edge]]'''''

Derek Sherinian was voted "Best Keyboardist" in Metal Edge magazine's 1998 Readers' Choice Awards.<ref>Metal Edge, August 1999</ref>

'''Metal Storm'''

The webzine Metal Storm honored Dream Theater with an award in 2009, when ''Black Clouds & Silver Linings'' was voted Best Progressive Metal Album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalstorm.net/awards/archive.php?year=2009|title=Metal Storm Awards 2009 - Metal Storm|website=Metalstorm.net|accessdate=May 12, 2019}}</ref>

'''''The Prog Report'''''

On July 13, 2015, ''The Prog Report'' ranked ''Images and Words'' at #1 on their "Top Prog Albums of the Last 25 Years". Four other Dream Theater albums made the list; ''Scenes from a Memory'' placed at #3, ''Six Degrees of Inner Turbulence'' at #14, ''Awake'' at #18, and ''Train of Thought'' at #38.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://progreport.com/top-50-prog-albums-1990-2015/ |title=Top 50 Prog Albums 1990-2015 |publisher=The Prog Report |date=July 13, 2015 |accessdate=January 30, 2016}}</ref>

===Other recognition===
* At Dream Theater's [[Salt Lake City]] show, Governor [[Jon Huntsman, Jr.]] signed a proclamation making July 30, 2007, "Dream Theater Day".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=77886 |title=Utah Governor Declares Dream Theater Day - July 31, 2007 |accessdate=November 2, 2010 |work=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101004134053/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=77886 |archivedate=October 4, 2010 }}</ref>
* Dream Theater were featured twice in the Xbox 360 Game With Fame event. They played ''[[Halo 3]]'' in December 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xbox.com/en-US/community/calendar/gamewithfame/2007/1218-dreamtheater-recap.htm|title=Xbox.com – Game with Fame – Game with Fame: Dream Theater Recap|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081015200636/http://www.xbox.com/en-US/community/calendar/gamewithfame/2007/1218-dreamtheater-recap.htm|archivedate=October 15, 2008}}</ref> and ''[[Call of Duty: World at War]]'' in June 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xbox.com/en-US/community/calendar/gamewithfame/2009/0620-dreamtheatre.htm|title=Xbox.com – Events  – Play Call of Duty: World at War with Dream Theater|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619014130/http://www.xbox.com/en-US/community/calendar/gamewithfame/2009/0620-dreamtheatre.htm|archivedate=June 19, 2009}}</ref>
* In November 2010, Dream Theater was inducted into the [[Long Island Music Hall of Fame]].

